ike to go to South Shields but I - I never had the money for to go. And I was rather independent, I wouldn't go and ask for it. And I would go and I'd walk to South Shields. Now I always remember, I'd go - walk to South Shields, I'd walk it, play on the s
a
nds. No money. And I would get hungry. And I would - oh I would go and try and get something to eat. Well I would get as far as maybe Tyne dock. You go down a back lane or something and see a kid with a great big slice of jam and bread. You see, that made
 
us hungrier. So I'd say to the kid, he'd be - the same size as myself, not - not any little kid, I wouldn't - same size as you, I says, are you going to give a bit of your bread? I'm hungry. Piece of bread. I'll watch it. I says, give us a bit else I'll t
ake it off you. You see. So he says, you want to try? So I get stuck in and take his bread off him. I give him half of it back thought. Wouldn't get it all. What would - what would you do if you were hungry?
